I made this last night to serve with fresh bratwurst boiled in beer and onion, then grilled. I made is essentially true to the recipe, rosemary and all. I did modify the bacon because there was no weight specified and I have my bacon cut somewhat thicker than the norm. The vinegar I used was white wine vinegar and I cut down the salt and sugar a bit. I used skin-on new crop redskin potatoes that I sliced to 4 mm in a food processor. I boiled them about 5 minutes in salted water and drained them and poured the dressing, bacon crumbles and fresh parsley. I think the sweet, salty, tart flavors were in balance. The comments about "rosemary not being 'typical' were kind of amusing to me. It is an ethnic dish. Isn't saying 'not typical' pretty much the case when making a food that you have not prepared before? The first time I made Steak au Poivre, deglazing the pan with Cognac was not typical for my family, either but they loved it.

